{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3b009271-854d-4d52-b3b4-778d3973ad18","content":"## Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the Inspector with `npx`:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (default `http://localhost:6274`) that proxies to your server over stdio.\n\n**Key steps in the Inspector UI:**\n\n1. **Connect** — click \"Connect\" to initialize the MCP session.\n2. **List Tools** — navigate to the \"Tools\" tab to see registered tools.\n3. **Test a Tool** — select a tool, fill in the JSON arguments, and click \"Run\" to invoke it.\n4. **Inspect Messages** — the bottom pane shows raw JSON-RPC request/response traffic for debugging.\n\n**Tips:**\n\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout** only. Any logging or debug output must go to **stderr** (e.g., `Console.Error.WriteLine()`), otherwise the protocol framing breaks.\n- Pass extra environment variables with `-e`:\n  ```bash\n  npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector -e MY_VAR=value dotnet run --project ./src/MyServer\n  ```\n- If your server is already built, point directly at the DLL:\n  ```bash\n  npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet /path/to/MyServer.dll\n  ```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1c8291ac-b651-42fc-9110-4018b46cfb05","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling — I can answer this directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about using the MCP Inspector with a stdio-based C# MCP server.","outputTokens":429,"requestId":"F3CB:9B30C:1082F7:14B7F8:69F54DE1"},"id":"f5fb0520-10a9-4d3c-9451-1d5ef0ee0e32","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:05:49.992Z","parentId":"dfc0bab1-7b0e-4981-ab8c-109c6d5593d9"}
